ile too much nitrogen transforms ecosystems profoundly. The California Nitrogen Assessment is the first comprehensive account of nitrogen flows, practices, and policies for California, encompassing all nitrogen flows-not just those associated with agriculture-and their impacts on ecosystem services and human wellbeing. How California handles nitrogen issues will be of interest nationally and internationally, and the goal of the assessment is to link science with action and to produce information that affects both future policy and solutions for addressing nitrogen pollution. This book also provides a model for application of integrated ecosystem assessment methods at regional and state (subnational) levels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBiodiversity conservationxCaliforniaxCalifornia. 0aNitrogen cyclexEnvironmental aspectsxCalifornia. 0aNitrogen fertilizersxGovernment policyxCalifornia. 0aNitrogenxEnvironmental aspectsxCalifornia. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aTomich, Thomas P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016z978311066754708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520962231423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520962231.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066754-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles